  <doc:section id="swallowing">
    <doc:title><templ:date>1574/05/01</templ:date> &mdash; An Unladen Swallow</doc:title>
      
    <p>Under a bright Yorkshire sun, Merlin and Arthur strolled the battlements of Camelot. Merlin turned to Arthur and commented, "Regard the swallows in yon field, your majesty. They dive like falling stones."</p>
      
    <p>"Indeed," Arthur replied as he tossed a stone from the wall and watched it fall. "They even seem to fall faster at times. Surely though it is not possible for something as light as a swallow to fall faster than something as heavy a stone."</p>
      
    <p>"I must confess I do not know, though it is truly an interesting question," Merlin replied. "I will investigate."</p>
      
    <p>Several months pass and the magician and the king were once again walking the battlements. Looking out over a rain drenched field, Merlin said, "Do you recall when we discussed stones and swallows?"</p>
      
    <p>"I think of it frequently as we round this corner. Why? Have you learned more?"</p>
      
    <p>"I've found references to an ancient book, <cite>The Belat Missan</cite>, that should contain the answer. The book is likely still in Christendom, but I don't think the question warrants a search."</p>
      
    <p>"Perhaps it does," replied Arthur. "The knights are restless in these peaceful times. The rain traps them in the castle all day. They could do well with a quest."</p>
      
    <p>"Well," replied Merlin, "I know that Camelot would certainly do well with some quiet. I think it is an excellent idea."</p>
      
    <p>The next week, Arthur sent his four bravest knights to the four corners of the world to search for <cite>The Belat Missan</cite>.</p>
      
