  <doc:section id="uuhi">
    <doc:title><templ:date/> &mdash; Universal Uniform Holon Identifier (<acronym title="Universal Uniform Holon Identifier">UUHI</acronym>)</doc:title>
    
    <p>A Universal Uniform Holon Identifier (UUHI) occupies the namespace ∅:<em>x</em>. Programmers can write systems in terms of "consentual" variables.</p>
    
    <p>Organizations then create naming conventions for different types Universal Uniform Holon Name.</p>
    
    <doc:section id="holon">
      <doc:title><templ:date/> &mdash; What's a Holon?</doc:title>
      
      <p>Fundamental units represent a limit on the systemic knowledge of a science.</p>
      
      <p>Because cyberspace is an imaginary domain, its fundamental unit be assigned a real value &mdash; the bit. Digital information is defined as knowledge that can be expressed as a string of bits.</p>

      <p>A holon is a unit of thought. This paper uses the term as:</p>
      
      <ul class="analogies">
	<li>quark:quantum physics</li>
	<li>atom:astrophysics</li>
	<li>bit:cyberspace</li>
	<li>honon:<a href="#no&#xF6;sphere">no&#xF6;sphere</a></li>
      </ul>
    </doc:section>
    
    <doc:section id="holon">
      <doc:title>Holon Naming</doc:title>
    </doc:section>
    
    <doc:section id="no&#xF6;sphere">
      <doc:title>What is the "No&#xF6;sphere?"</doc:title>
      
      <p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No&#xF6;sphere">No&#xF6;sphere</a> is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teilhard_de_Chardin">Pierre Teilhard de Chardin</a>'s, term for the "sphere of all thought." In this paper, the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No&#xF6;sphere">No&#xF6;sphere</a> refers to every possible idea.</p>
      
      <p>Recall the space of things representable by <em>n</em> bits grows at the rate 2<sup><em>n</em></sup>:</p>
      
      <templ:templ name="figure">
	<templ:var name="name">Positive Powers of Two</templ:var>
	<templ:var name="height">300px</templ:var>
      </templ:templ>
      
      <p>For example, in 2009 there's a &gt; 99% or the word "watermelons" in this sentence is stored in 11 bytes somewhere. At eight bits per byte and two states per bit (0 and 1), those 11 bytes can represent:</p>

      <div>2<sup>11*8</sup> = 2<sup>88</sup> = 309,485,009,821,345,068,724,781,056 possibilities</div>

      <p>This paper is a holon &mdash; a discrete blob of information with a creator (<a href="$/../smtp"><tip:author/></a>).</p>

      <p>Spotspace is a way of organizing information. Locations for information are called spots. Each spot is connected to other spots by semantic associations.</p>
      
      <p>Every spot in spotspace has a unique name.</p>
    </doc:section>
  </doc:section>
  
  <doc:section id="resources">
    <doc:title>Computing Resources</doc:title>
    
    <p>Show lasers interferring.</p>
    
    <p>Computers and lasers provide resources in roughly the same way: a raw stream of power. Whether it's light or computing power, they only have two states on or off. You can set up interference if you like, but all you're going to possibly do is reduce overall efficiency.</p>
  </doc:section>
